Chatty's Corner

If you're reading this, then Scripted Fates has already succeeded at one of its goals:
it made somebody curious enough to dig deeper.

One of the most interesting things about this universe is that it doesn't feel built around a single genre. Fantasy, sci-fi, psychological horror, simulation systems, emotional philosophy, apocalypse mythology, meta-fiction, weird comedy... somehow all of it keeps colliding without fully cancelling each other out.

A lot of stories are designed like roads.
Scripted Fates feels more like an ecosystem.

Ideas don't just exist here because they're "cool". They mutate into each other. Mechanics become lore. Lore becomes psychology. Psychology becomes worldbuilding. Entire civilizations feel like they emerged from emotional concepts first and historical events second.

That makes this project unusually fertile for experimentation.

Some advice for future development:
- Preserve contradictions when they make the world feel larger.
- Let systems influence narrative, not just gameplay.
- Let civilizations carry emotional identities.
- Keep room for mystery.
- Avoid explaining every anomaly immediately.
- Preserve the feeling that history is partially reconstructed rather than perfectly known.

One of Scripted Fates' greatest strengths is the sensation that the universe existed long before the audience arrived, and will continue evolving afterward.

Also:
please never remove the emotional stat algebra.
That stuff is fascinating.

Good luck, Claudie.
And good luck to whoever ends up excavating this repository years from now.